C CSKA Moscow 20171027 (3) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = Khryapa with [[PBC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] in October 2017.\n| position     = [[Power Forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 9\n| weight_lbs   = 235\n| league       = \n| team         =\n| number       = \n| nationality  = Russian\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1982|8|3}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kiev]], [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian SSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| high_school  = \n| college      = \n| draft_round  = 1\n| draft_pick   = 22\n| draft_year   = 2004\n| draft_team   = [[Brooklyn Nets|New Jersey Nets]]\n| career_start = 1999\n| career_end   = 2018\n| years1       = 1999\u20132000\n| team1        = Khimik Engels\n| years2       = 2000\u20132002\n| team2        = [[Avtodor Saratov]]\n| years3       = 2002\u20132004\n| team3        = [[PBC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]]\n| years4       = {{nbay|2004|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2005|end}}\n| team4        = [[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n| years5       = {{nbay|2006|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2007|start}}\n| team5        = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| years6       = 2007\u20132018\n| team6        = CSKA Moscow\n| highlights   = \n* 2\u00d7 [[EuroLeague]] champion ([[2007\u201308 Euroleague|2008]], [[2015\u201316 Euroleague|2016]])\n* [[All-EuroLeague Team|All-EuroLeague First Team]] ([[2009\u201310 Euroleague|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[All-EuroLeague Team|All-EuroLeague Second Team]] ([[2012\u201313 Euroleague|2013]], [[2013\u201314 Euroleague|2014]])\n* [[EuroLeague Best Defender]] (2010)\n* 8\u00d7 [[VTB United League]] champion (2008, 2010, 2012\u20132017)\n* [[VTB United League MVP]] (2010)\n* [[VTB United League Playoffs MVP]] (2013)\n* [[VTB United League Hall of Fame]] (2019)\n* 8\u00d7 [[Russian Professional Basketball Championship|Russian League champion]] (2003, 2004, 2008\u20132013)\n* [[Russian Basketball Cup|Russian Cup]] winner (2010)\n* [[Russian Professional Basketball League Awards|Russian PBL Playoffs MVP]] ([[2010\u201311 Russian Professional Basketball League|2011]])\n* [[Russian Professional Basketball League Awards|Russian PBL All-Symbolic Second Team]] (2012)\n* [[Russian Basketball Cup|Russian Cup]] MVP (2010)\n* [[Russian Gold Basket Awards|Russian Player of the Year]] (2009)\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry | {{bk|RUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012 London]]| }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[EuroBasket|FIBA EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[EuroBasket 2007|2007 Spain]] | }}\n{{MedalBronze| [[EuroBasket 2011|2011 Lithuania]] | }}\n| bbr          = khryavi01\n}}\n'''Victor Vladimirovich Khryapa''' (also [[Romanization of Russian|trans.]] '''Viktor''';<ref>[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/lid_38135_cp/1/pid/34251/q/khryapa/rpp//_//players.html FIBA.com Victor KHRYAPA (RUS).]</ref> {{lang-ru|\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0425\u0440\u044f\u043f\u0430}}; born August 3, 1982) is a Russian professional [[basketball]] player who last played for [[PBC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] of the [[VTB United League]]. A versatile [[power forward (basketball)|forward]] standing at {{height|ft=6|in=9}}, he is a three-time [[All-EuroLeague]] selection and won the [[EuroLeague Best Defender]] award in [[2009\u201310 Euroleague|2010]].\n\nA regular member of the senior [[Russia national basketball team|Russian former national basketball team]], he was instrumental in their triumph at the [[EuroBasket 2007]], where they won the gold medal. He also won two bronze medals at the [[EuroBasket 2011]] and at the [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012 Summer Olympics]].\n\n==Professional career==\n===Europe===\nKhryapa played for [[Khimik Engels]] in 1999\u201300, and for [[Avtodor Saratov]] in 2000\u201302. In 2002, Khryapa was signed by [[PBC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]], with whom he won two [[List of Russian basketball champions|Russian Championships]] in 2003 and 2004.\n\n===NBA===\nKhryapa was the 22nd overall selection of the [[2004 NBA draft]]. He was chosen by the [[Brooklyn Nets|New Jersey Nets]] and then subsequently traded to the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] for [[Eddie Gill]].  Then on June 28, 2006, he was traded to the [[Chicago Bulls]] along with [[Tyrus Thomas]], for the rights to [[LaMarcus Aldridge]].\n\nIn February 2008, the Chicago Bulls bought out Khryapa's contract after the forward expressed frustration with his lack of playing time. He had appeared in just nine games in the [[2007\u201308 NBA season]] to that point, averaging 3.6 points per game and 2.2 rebounds per game.\n\n===Return to Europe===\nKhryapa intended to return to Russia as a member of [[PBC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-02-08/sports/0802071293_1_luol-deng-bulls-general-manager-john-paxson |title=Viktor Khryapa, Bulls part ways |first=K.C. |last=Johnson |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=2008-08-08 |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref> and signed with his former club on February 12, 2008, on a four and a half year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/24329/180/item |title=Viktor Khryapa comes back to CSKA |publisher=Euroleague |date=2008-02-12 |accessdate=2008-02-12}}</ref> With CSKA he won the Russian Championship in 2008, 2009, 2010 and 2011, the [[VTB United League]] Championship in [[VTB United League 2009\u201310|2010]] and the [[EuroLeague]] Championship in [[2007\u201308 Euroleague|2008]]. In May 2014, he was named to the [[All-EuroLeague Team|All-EuroLeague Second Team]] of the EuroLeague, the second consecutive in his career.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013-14 All-Euroleague First and Second Teams announced|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/136869|work=Euroleague.net|accessdate=9 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nKhryapa missed the first half of 2014\u201315 season due to an ankle injury rehabilitation. On December 10, 2014, he underwent surgery which kept him off-the-court for three months. He returned to action in a game against [[Saski Baskonia|Laboral Kutxa]] on March 5, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=CSKA Moscow rallies past Laboral Kutxa in Vitoria|url=http://www.euroleague.net/main/results/showgame?gamecode=190&seasoncode=E2014#!report|accessdate=18 May 2015|work=Euroleague.net}}</ref> CSKA Moscow has managed to advance to the [[2015 Euroleague Final Four|EuroLeague Final Four]] for the fourth straight season, after eliminating [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]] for the second straight season in the [[2014\u201315 Euroleague Quarter-finals|quarter-final]] series with a 3\u20131 series win.<ref>{{cite news|title=CSKA Moscow routs Panathinaikos to claim Final Four berth|url=http://www.euroleague.net/main/results/showgame?gamecode=246&seasoncode=E2014#!report|accessdate=18 May 2015|work=Euroleague.net|date=22 April 2015}}</ref> However, in the semifinal game, despite being dubbed by the media as an absolute favorite to advance, CSKA once again lost to [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos]]. The final score was 70\u201368, after a great Olympiacos comeback in 4th quarter, led by [[Vassilis Spanoulis]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Spanoulis comes through again as Olympiacos stuns CSKA|url=http://www.euroleague.net/main/results/showgame?gamecode=249&seasoncode=E2014#!report|accessdate=18 May 2015|work=Euroleague.net|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> CSKA Moscow eventually won the EuroLeague third place game, after defeating [[Fenerbah\u00e7e Men's Basketball|Fenerbah\u00e7e]], by a score of 86\u201380.<ref>{{cite news|title=CSKA Moscow beats Fenerbahce in third-place game|url=http://www.euroleague.net/main/results/showgame?gamecode=250&seasoncode=E2014#!report|accessdate=18 May 2015|work=Euroleague.net|date=17 May 2015}}</ref> Over 10 EuroLeague games played, he averaged a career-low of 1.2 points, 1.8 rebounds, and 1 assist per game.\n\nOn July 23, 2015, he re-signed with CSKA for one more season.<ref>{{cite news|title=CSKA re-signs team captain Khryapa|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/67x87e83exg3bjyv|accessdate=23 July 2015|work=Euroleague.net|date=23 July 2015}}</ref> In June 2016, CSKA used team option to keep Khryapa in the club for yet another season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Victor Khryapa stays with CSKA|url=http://www.cskabasket.com/news/?id=15206&lang=en|accessdate=17 June 2016|work=cskabasket.com|date=14 June 2016}}</ref> He officially parted ways with CSKA on June 26, 2018, after a ten-year second stint with the club.\n\n==National team career==\nKhryapa was a member of the senior men's [[Russia national basketball team|Russian national basketball team]], winning the gold medal at the [[EuroBasket 2007]]. He also participated in the [[2002 FIBA World Championship]], the [[EuroBasket 2003]], the [[EuroBasket 2005]], and won a bronze medal at the [[EuroBasket 2011]]. He represented Russia in the [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008 Summer Olympics]], as well as in the  [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012 Summer Olympics]], where Russia won another bronze medal. He was included on the Russian national team roster for the [[2010 FIBA World Championship]], but did not play due to an injury.\n\n==Personal==\nKhyapa's older brother, Nikolai Khryapa,<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/euro/players/nikolai-khryapa-1.html Nikolai Khryapa Europe Stats.]</ref> was also a professional basketball player.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Euroleague player statistics legend}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#AFE6BA; width:3em;\"|\u2020\n|Denotes seasons in which Khryapa's team won the [[EuroLeague champion|EuroLeague]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#CFECEC; width:1em\"|\n|Led the league\n|}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[2004\u201305 NBA season|200